title: Ada Lovelace
summary: Ada Lovelace was an English mathematician and writer known for early work on Charles Babbage's analytical engine and for notes that anticipated software concepts.

title: Grace Hopper
summary: Grace Hopper was an American computer scientist and United States Navy rear admiral who helped pioneer compiler design and popularized machine-independent programming languages.

title: Alan Turing
summary: Alan Turing was a British mathematician and logician whose work in computation, cryptanalysis, and artificial intelligence profoundly shaped modern computer science.

title: Marie Curie
summary: Marie Curie was a physicist and chemist who conducted pioneering research on radioactivity and became the first person to win Nobel Prizes in two sciences.

title: Maya Angelou
summary: Maya Angelou was an American poet, memoirist, and civil rights activist whose autobiographical works and performances influenced literature and public discourse.

title: William Shakespeare
summary: William Shakespeare was an English playwright, poet, and actor whose plays and sonnets remain foundational works in world literature and theater.

title: Frida Kahlo
summary: Frida Kahlo was a Mexican painter recognized for deeply personal self-portraits that blended realism, symbolism, and reflections on identity and pain.

title: History of the Internet
summary: The history of the Internet traces networks developed for resilient communication into the global infrastructure for information exchange and digital services.

title: Renaissance
summary: The Renaissance was a period of cultural, artistic, and scientific revival in Europe that followed the Middle Ages and transformed intellectual life.

title: Roman Empire
summary: The Roman Empire was the post-republican period of ancient Rome marked by territorial expansion, centralized authority, and enduring legal and engineering legacies.

title: Climate change
summary: Climate change refers to long-term shifts in global or regional climate patterns, largely linked in recent decades to human-generated greenhouse gas emissions.

title: Amazon rainforest
summary: The Amazon rainforest is the world's largest tropical forest, known for its biodiversity, climate influence, and central role in regional ecosystems.

title: Solar energy
summary: Solar energy is radiant light and heat from the Sun harnessed through technologies such as photovoltaics, concentrated solar power, and thermal systems.

title: Machine learning
summary: Machine learning is a field of artificial intelligence focused on algorithms that learn patterns from data to make predictions or decisions without explicit rules.

title: Quantum mechanics
summary: Quantum mechanics is a fundamental physical theory describing nature at atomic and subatomic scales where probabilities and wave-particle behavior dominate.

title: Mount Everest
summary: Mount Everest is Earth's highest mountain above sea level, located in the Himalayas on the border between Nepal and the Tibet Autonomous Region.

title: Pacific Ocean
summary: The Pacific Ocean is the largest and deepest of Earth's oceanic divisions, stretching from the Arctic to the Southern Ocean and connecting many ecosystems.

title: World Health Organization
summary: The World Health Organization is a specialized United Nations agency responsible for international public health coordination and global health guidance.

title: Artificial intelligence
summary: Artificial intelligence is the study and development of systems that perform tasks associated with human cognition, including reasoning, language, and planning.

title: Biodiversity
summary: Biodiversity describes the variety of life across genes, species, and ecosystems, and is central to ecological resilience and long-term environmental stability.
